## PR Description
**Title**: Allow one policy to apply to many settings

**Body**:
## Summary\n\nAdds a `policyReference` mechanism so a single enterprise policy can govern more than one setting, and uses it to gate the Claude and Codex agents consistently across the **editor window** and the **Agents window**.\n\n## What changed\n\n- **`policyReference` (config layer).** A setting can declare `policyReference: { name }` to be governed by a policy *owned* (declared via `policy`) by another setting. The owner stays the single source of truth for the policy's type/metadata/runtime; a reference only contributes the policy name so the setting is gated and the OS policy watcher observes it. `ConfigurationRegistry` keeps owners 1:1 and adds `getPolicyReferenceConfigurations()` (name → subordinate settings); declaring both `policy` and `policyReference` is rejected.\n- **Claude.** Reuse the existing `Claude3PIntegration` policy (owned by the Copilot extension setting `github.copilot.chat.claudeAgent.enabled`) via `policyReference` on `chat.agentHost.claudeAgent.enabled` and `sessions.chat.claudeAgent.enabled`.\n- **Codex.** Add `Codex3PIntegration`, owned by `chat.agentHost.codexAgent.enabled` (the single runtime that surfaces Codex in both windows). Both honor `chat_preview_features_enabled === false`.\n- **IPC-safe serialization.** `AbstractPolicyService.serialize()` strips the non-cloneable `value()` callback (`toSerializablePolicyDefinition`) so policies registered in the main process survive structured-clone to the renderer; `updatePolicyDefinitions` replaces per name so a late-registering owner supersedes a reference.\n- **Tooling.** The exported policy catalog and the **Developer: Policy Diagnostics** report now list the settings each policy governs.\n\n## Testing\n\nUnit tests cover owner/reference resolution, late-owner supersede, owner-removal fallback, and callback-free serialization. Manually verified with a macOS MDM profile that a single `Claude3PIntegration` / `Codex3PIntegration` value gates the owner plus its references across both windows.

