## PR Description
**Title**: Use AHP ping for active liveness on remote agent host connections

**Body**:
Replaces the previous per-request timeout on remote agent host connections with a periodic ping-based liveness check, modelled after `PersistentProtocol`'s socket keep-alive.\n\n## What\n\n- New AHP `ping` request is issued every 5s by `RemoteAgentHostProtocolClient`.\n- If no inbound message has been received for 20s, the client force-closes the connection. `RemoteAgentHostService` then reconnects via its existing exponential backoff.\n- Reuses `LoadEstimator` (now exported from `ipc.net.ts`) to suppress the force-close when local CPU is pegged — same heuristic `PersistentProtocol` uses to avoid blaming the remote for our own JS event-loop stalls. Also handles laptop sleep/wake correctly: the timer fires once after wake but the wall-clock comparison stays accurate.\n- The old per-request timeout (originally added to detect a disconnected remote) is removed.\n\n## Why\n\nThe per-request timeout only fired while a request was in flight, so a connection that went idle and silently dropped wouldn't be noticed. An active ping covers both:\n- **Keep-alive** — keeps idle-timeout intermediaries (proxies, load balancers) from killing the connection.\n- **Liveness** — a hung AH process won't run its dispatch loop to answer, so a healthy TCP socket with a frozen peer trips the timeout. A silently-dead transport trips the same way. Either way: drop and reconnect.\n\n## Notes\n\n- The protocol-side `ping` command is in [microsoft/agent-host-protocol#119](https://github.com/microsoft/agent-host-protocol/pull/119). This PR depends on that landing + the next sync into vscode.\n- Servers without `ping` support are tolerated: the `MethodNotFound` error response is itself inbound traffic, so liveness is satisfied without any client-side branching.\n- Behavior against a permanently-hung AH: reconnect attempts back off to 30s and continue indefinitely (no grace deadline, unlike remote EH's 3-hour cap). Could revisit if it becomes a problem in the wild.\n\n(Written by Copilot)

